sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1833002
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This part produces GFP in the presence of T3 RNA polymerase. It contains a T3 promoter, a strong RBS, the coding region for GFP, and a double terminator. The GFP is a mutant known as GFPmut3b, and the original citation is as follows:
Cormack, B.P., Valdivia, R.H., and S. Falkow. FACS-optimized mutants of green fluorescent protein (GFP). Gene 173: 33-38 (1996).
(http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378111995006850)
It has a maximum excitation at 501 nm and maximum emission at 511 nm. For more information, see part BBa_E0040.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Konstantin Borisov
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The RBS-GFP-terminator was obtained from as part BBa_E0840 from the 2015 Distribution (Plate 2, Well 24D). The T3 promoter was obtained as two short oligonucleotides annealed to form sticky ends. The part containing GFP was then cut with EcoRI and XbaI, and ligated with the annealed oligos to form the completed part.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The part containing GFP was cut with EcoRI and XbaI, and ligated with the annealed oligos to form the completed part. Note that due to the choice of cloning technique, a Biobrick scar site remains between the promoter and RBS.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0030
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Strong RBS based on Ron Weiss thesis. Strength is considered relative to <bb_part>BBa_B0031</bb_part>, <bb_part>BBa_B0032</bb_part>, <bb_part>BBa_B0033</bb_part>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix ("orig" in figure 4-14 of Ron Weiss thesis).

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1833997
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is a part used as a building block for T3 driven expression. However, this part uses a special cloning method with the following synthesized nucleotides: pT3sense: aattcgcggccgcttctagaaattaaccctcactaaagggagaa pT3antisense: ctagttctccctttagtgagggttaatttctagaagcggccgcg The following method can be used to insert pProt before a desired Biobrick part (which should contain an RBS at minimum and preferably a cds and terminator): 1. Cut the desired plasmid with EcoRI and XbaI. Purify the plasmid with a method of your choice (both gel purification and PCR purification kits from Qiagen serve to remove the short undesired oligonucleotide from the digestion). 2. Be sure that your oligos have 5' phosphorylation (treat unphosphorylated oligos with T4 Polynucleotide Kinase). Then, anneal the two oligos by slowly cooling from 98C to room temperature. 3. Finally, ligate the cut plasmid with the annealed oligos by using a 1:10 molar ratio of plasmid to insert. 4. Transform the ligation reaction into E. coli, and plate. 5. Pick colonies, and verify the success of the cloning with sequencing or PCR. (Doing a diagnostic digest is not recommended as the size of the original plasmid and the desired plasmid are very similar.) 6. Add a composite part to the iGEM registry by using this part with the original protein coding part, checking the box to create without a scar, as this part contains a modified scar.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Konstantin Borisov
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Synthesized oligonucleotides as described on main page.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: When ligating with a cut plasmid, this leaves a modified Biobrick scar between the T7 promoter and original Biobrick part, which is included in the sequence of this part.
